# Next.js Architecture

## Router

- **App Router only.** There is no `pages/` directory and it must never be created.
- File-based routing lives entirely in `frontend/app/`.

## Page Components

- All page and leaf route components are **`"use client"`** — they use React Query for data and local `useState` for UI state.
- Do not use React Server Components for pages that display dynamic data.
- Dynamic route params are typed as `{ params: { id: string } }` in the page props.

```tsx
// canonical pattern — app/bank-transactions/[id]/page.tsx
"use client";
export default function BankTransactionPage({ params }: { params: { id: string } }) { … }
```

## Root Layout

- `app/layout.tsx` is the single root layout. It wraps `<QueryProvider>` and `<Sidebar>`.
- **Do not add new providers** anywhere else — place them here if a new global provider is needed.
- `<html lang="en">` is set in the root layout; do not add another `<html>` tag.

## API Route Handlers (proxy layer)

- Every Next.js API route in `app/api/` is a **thin proxy**. Its only job is to call one of the helpers from `lib/proxy.ts` and return the result.
- Use `proxyGet`, `proxyPost`, `proxyPut`, `proxyPatch`, `proxyDelete` from `@/lib/proxy`.
- Forward `searchParams` for GET list endpoints:

```ts
// canonical pattern — app/api/bank-transactions/route.ts
import { proxyGet } from "@/lib/proxy";
export async function GET(req: Request) {
  return proxyGet(req);
}
```

- For endpoints with a path parameter, use `NextRequest` and pass the id explicitly:

```ts
// app/api/receipts/[id]/route.ts
import { proxyGet, proxyDelete } from "@/lib/proxy";
export async function GET(_: Request, { params }: { params: { id: string } }) {
  return proxyGet(_, { pathSuffix: params.id });
}
```

- **Never add business logic** to route handlers — validation, transformation, or DB calls all belong in the backend.

## Path Alias

- `@/*` maps to `frontend/*` (configured in `tsconfig.json`).
- Use the alias for all intra-project imports: `@/lib/api`, `@/components/ui`, etc.

## Navigation

- Internal navigation uses Next.js `<Link>` — do not use `<a href>` for internal routes.
- Programmatic navigation uses `useRouter()` from `next/navigation`.

## Canonical References

- `frontend/app/layout.tsx` — root layout with providers
- `frontend/app/bank-transactions/page.tsx` — representative list page
- `frontend/app/bank-transactions/[id]/page.tsx` — representative detail page
- `frontend/app/api/receipts/[id]/route.ts` — thin proxy with path param
- `frontend/app/api/bank-transactions/route.ts` — thin proxy forwarding searchParams
- `frontend/lib/proxy.ts` — all proxy helper implementations
